attributes.definition: The "local" accession number that you use for your laboratory's database. This number should link EXACTLY to the genetic data you are providing for this sample. It must be unique among the numbers that your lab is providing.
Firstname Lastname (the PI on the grant that generated this data)

Local name of site. Something that could be found by Google, e.g. city, town, ocean, etc. You must enter a value for this to the best level of precision that you are confident about. A site name like "Sanur" is good. "Indonesia" is fine if that is all you know, or "The Pacific Ocean". If you have no idea where the sample came from, please enter "Earth". Required.
The full scientific name of the phylum in which the taxon is classified. Required.
Decimal Degrees. If you don't have this information, you must enter something into the locality field to the best known precision.
Decimal Degrees. If you don't have this information, you must enter something into the locality field to the best known precision.

Coordinate uncertainy in meters. For pooled data include the greatest distance in meters over which pooled samples were collected with the decimal latitude and decimal longitude representing the mid point.

A description or reference to the methods used to determine the spatial footprint, coordinates, and uncertainties (e.g. GPS, Approximated from Google Maps, Based on locality name search in Google Maps (Ben Morris' script) etc.)
YYYY (the year collected). For pooled samples this is the earliest month of collection.
MM (the month collected).  For pooled samples this is the earliest month of collection.
DD (the day collected). For pooled samples this is the earliest month of collection.
The full scientific name of the genus in which the taxon is classified.
The name of the first or species epithet of the scientificName.
Please include any permit information (agency, permit#, etc) as a text string
Morphology, Genetic, Other.
The country where the sample was found. Must be found in associated list in "lists" tab.
The age class or life stage of the biological individual(s) at the time the Occurrence was recorded. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary.
The sex of the biological individual(s) represented in the Occurrence. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary. See associated list on "lists" tab.
A list (concatenated and separated) of the tissue types sampled from this individual, together with any tissue identifiers that were assigned to them
The number of individuals represented in the material sample. The default is 1.  An individual count greater than 1 indicates this is a pooled sample.
The state or province where the sample was found.
The island where the sample was found.
The island group or archipelago where the sample was found.

The process by which the biological individual(s) represented in the Occurrence became established at the location. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary. See associated list in "lists" tab.
Habitat from which the sample was collected.  The list of habitats are drawn mainly from the Environment Ontology (ENVO) biome classification.  Please pick from the associated list in "lists" tab.
Information about the microhabitat from which the sample was collected. E.g. Forereef, coral head
Substrate from which the individual was sampled. This could be abiotic or biotic (host organism).
In Meters. Use with maximum depth to bracket the range of depth at which the sample was taken. In meters (positive values below surface)
In Meters. Use with minimum depth to bracket the range of depth at which the sample was taken. In meters (positive values below surface)
In Meters. Use with maximum distance above surface to bracket the range of height at which the sample was taken in meters (positive values above surface)
In Meters. Use with minimum distance above surface to bracket the range of height at which the sample was taken in meters (positive values above surface)
A list (concatenated and separated) of hosts/parasites/symbionts of the sampled individual.
Identification # (AphiaID) for Worms database (http://www.marinespecies.org/). Please try to provide this or the genus/species.
In Grams. Referring to the weight of the organism from which the sample was derived
In Centimeters. Referring to the length of the organism from which the sample was derived
The full scientific name of the class in which the taxon is classified.
The full scientific name of the order in which the taxon is classified.
The full scientific name of the family in which the taxon is classified.
The name of the lowest or terminal infraspecific epithet of the scientificName, excluding any rank designation.
Common name and/or native name
Comments or notes about the taxon or name.
Most commonly used acronym for your university, agency or institution
Granting body and grant number, can be in a delimited list.
If your sample has already been assigned an identifier by another database, for instance, a collections management database, use the occurrenceID field to store this identifier.
An identifier (preferably unique) for the record within the data set or collection.
A list (concatenated and separated) of identifiers (publication, global unique identifier, URI) of genetic sequence information associated with the Occurrence. Links to Genbank or DRYAD entries.
Full Name (can be list -- primary collector first, separate list by semicolons)
Full Name (A list (concatenated and separated) of names of people, groups, or organizations who assigned the Taxon to the subject.)
YYYY
MM
DD
A list (concatenated and separated) of preparations and preservation methods for a specimen. Example: "95% EtOH"; "Frozen"
Brief description of how the sample was taken. From Darwincore: The name of, reference to, or description of the method or protocol used during an Event.
A platename where the DNA extract is stored
The well on the plate where the DNA extract is stored
A unique identifier for the extraction (other than plate or well)
Other identifiers for this tissue.  E.g. tissue originated in another institution.
A list (concatenated and separated) of further identifiers for the container which holds the material sample.
Photos, videos etc of the individual. From Darwincore: A list (concatenated and separated) of identifiers (publication, global unique identifier, URI,DOI) of media associated with the Occurrence.

Any associated publications/references pertaining to this individual or its derivative tissues or sequences. The first place it was published is particularly relevant. From Darwincore: A list (concatenated and separated) of identifiers (publication, bibliographic reference, global unique identifier, URI) of literature associated with the Occurrence.
A list (concatenated and separated) of previous assignments of names to the Occurrence.
Any other relevant comments or notes about the sample itself.
Any notes taken in the field, or a link to those notes: population size, ecological info, etc.
A text string for notes that were written on the original label during collection
Sequence data for the material sample.
List of filenames to be uploaded to NCBI Genbank SRA

fields.definition: Random sequencing of the whole genome following non-pcr amplification
Random sequencing of the whole genome
Random sequencing of exonic regions selected from the genome
Random sequencing of a whole chromosome or other replicon isolated from a genome
Shotgun of pooled clones (usually BACs and Fosmids)
Sequencing of overlapping or distinct PCR or RT-PCR products
Sequencing intended to finish (close) gaps in existing coverage
Sequencing of hypersensitive sites, or segments of open chromatin that are more readily cleaved by DNaseI
Sequencing following treatment of DNA with bisulfite to convert cytosine residues to uracil depending on methylation status
Single pass sequencing of cDNA templates
Direct sequencing of methylated fractions sequencing strategy
Library strategy not listed (please include additional info in the “design description”)
Genomic DNA (includes PCR products from genomic DNA)
Transcription products or non genomic DNA (EST, cDNA, RT-PCR, screened libraries)
Other, unspecified, or unknown library source material (please include additional info in the “design description”)
Random selection by shearing or other method
Source material was selected by designed primers
Source material was selected by randomly generated primers
Source material was selected by reverse transcription PCR
Selection by hybridization in array or solution
Reproducible genomic subsets, often generated by restriction fragment size selection, containing a manageable number of loci to facilitate re-sampling
Selection of methylated DNA fragments using an antibody raised against 5-methylcytosine or 5-methylcytidine (m5C)
Physical selection of size appropriate targets
Other library enrichment, screening, or selection process (please include additional info in the “design description”)
Library enrichment, screening, or selection is not specified (please include additional info in the “design description”)
